engineering at the UIC College of Engineering   Photo  Jenny Fontaine Cerebrospinal fluid was obtained from the Human Brain and Spinal Fluid Resource Center  which banks fluid and tissue from deceased individuals  Berry  Dr  Ankit Mehta  assistant professor of neurosurgery and director of spinal oncology in the UIC College of Medicine  and their colleagues tested the cerebrospinal fluid from seven people without neurodegenerative disease  from    people with ALS  from three people with multiple sclerosis and from three people with an unknown neurodegenerative disease  multiple sclerosis or someone without neurodegenerative disease  We think the difference we see between older and younger ALS patients is driven by unique biochemical signatures we are picking up that correlate to inherited ALS  which usually produces symptoms before age     but only recently have we begun to examine its phononic properties as a way to detect diseases Bijentimala Keisham from the UIC College of Engineering  Steven Denyer  Pouyan Kheirkhan  Gregory Arnone  Abhiraj Bhimani and Dr  Ankit Mehta  from the department of neurosurgery in the UIC College of Medicine  Akop Seksenyan from the Rosalind Franklin University of Medicine and Science  Chicago  and Clive Svendsen from Cedars Sinai Medical Center  Los Angeles  are co authors on the paper This research was funded by grant N              from the Office of Naval Research  grant CMMI         from the National Science Foundation and a University of Illinois at Chicago Seed Grant  n nContact n nSharon Parmet n t t t t t t t             nsparmet uic edu n n n nCategories n nHealth Sciences Colleges  Research  n Contact  nSharon Parmet n t t t t t t t             nsparmet uic edu n Sharon Parmet sparmet uic edu Categories  nHealth Sciences Colleges  Research  Health Sciences Colleges Research Topics ALS  East Meets West  graphene  neurodegenerative disease ALS East Meets West graphene neurodegenerative disease  n nUIC Logo n n n n UIC Logo  n  